theorem:
\label{thm:main}
Fix a depth $L \ge 1$, input $d_{\operatorname{in}}$, and output  $d_{\operatorname{out}}\ge 1$ dimensions, Lipschitz activation functions $(\sigma^{(\ell)})_{\ell=1,\ldots, L}$, and consider a sequence of outputs $f^{(L)}_{(n)}: \mathbb{R}^{d_{\operatorname{in}}} \to \mathbb{R}^{d_{\operatorname{out}}}$ of a fully connected feedforward neural network (MLP) with hidden layer widths $n_\ell = n_\ell(n)$ such that 
$$\lim_{n\to \infty} \frac{n_\ell}{n} \in (0, \infty]  \quad \text{ for every $\ell=1, \ldots, L-1$,} $$
and i.i.d.\ Gaussian weights as in
\begin{equation}\label{eq:lecun} \EE\sqa{ (W^{(\ell)}_{i,j})^2} = \frac 1 {n_{\ell-1}} \quad \text{for every $\ell=1, \ldots, L$ and every $i$, $j$.} \end{equation}
--  also known as LeCun initialization. 

Then, for every compact input set $\mathcal{X} \subseteq \mathbb{R}^{d_{\operatorname{in}}}$, the rescaled output of the network
$$ x \in \mathcal{X} \mapsto \frac{1}{\sqrt{n}} f^{(L)}_{(n)}(x), $$
seen as a random element on $C(\mathcal{X},\mathbb{R}^{d_{out}})$, endowed with the topology of uniform convergence,
satisfies the LDP with speed $n$ and a suitable rate function given by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:rate-functional}
I_{\cX, \out}^{(L)} (z) = \sup_{\cX_0 \subset\cX \text{finite}} I_{\cX_0, \out}^{(L)}\bra{\pi_{\cX_0}(z)}.
\end{equation}

sketch:
The proof of the main theorem relies on an inductive argument on the number of layers, combining Cram\'er's theorem for empirical means of i.i.d.\ random variables with a careful analysis of the continuity properties of the neural network architecture, with a structure somewhat analogous to that of the functional CLT for MLPs. Concretely:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] Establish exponential tightness of the sequence $(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}} f^{(L)}_{(n)}(\cdot))_{n\geq 1}$ on $C(\mathcal{X},\mathbb{R}^{d_{out}})$, endowed with the uniform topology, using a variant of Schied's criterion … tailored to the layer-by-layer propagation of randomness and taking into account the sub-linear growth of activation functions.
\item[(ii)] Prove that for a fixed finite set of inputs, the LDP for the corresponding finite-dimensional network outputs holds, relying on Chaganty's lemma, combined with exponential equivalence arguments, and Cram\'er's theorem under local exponential moment assumptions, and crucially using epi-convergence techniques from convex analysis to ensure a needed joint lower semicontinuity.
\item[(iii)] Lift the finite-input LDPs to an LDP for the entire process via a standard application of the Dawson--G\"artner theorem and the inverse contraction principle.
\end{enumerate}

