sketch:
A proposed route to prove the main theorem is a naive proof by induction on the generation of $\Rb\wspc{T}$ from $T$: verify the conclusion in base cases ($f=T$, $f=\log(T)$, $\ldots$); then for a general series $f=\sum_{i<\alpha} r_i e^{\gamma_i}$, assume the conclusion for each map $x\mapsto \gamma_i\circ x$ and try to deduce monotonicity of $x\mapsto f\circ x$. This induction works very well for $f\in\Jb_\mathfrak{O}^{>0}$; more precisely:
\begin{prop}\label{monotonicity-J}
 For all $\gamma \in \Jb^{>0}$, the map $x \mapsto \gamma \circ x$ is strictly increasing.
\end{prop}
but falls short for the general case, so one additionally uses a very weak form of mean value property: for $\gamma\in\Jb_\mathfrak{O}^{>0}$ and $x>y>\mathbb R$,
\[
\frac{\gamma\circ x-\gamma\circ y}{x-y}\preceq \gamma'\circ y\quad \text{at least when}\quad \gamma\circ x-\gamma\circ y\preceq 1\ \text{or}\ (\gamma'\circ y)(x-y)\prec 1.
\]
This condition is almost trivial in the base cases $T,\log(T),\ldots$ because the corresponding functions $x\mapsto \log^{\circ n}(x)$ are strictly increasing and \emph{concave}. With this weak mean value property in hand, the rest of the induction is then relatively straightforward; in particular, one uses the following lemma:
\begin{lem}\label{weak-mvp}
 For all $\gamma \in \Jb^{>0}$ and all $x, y \in \Ub$ with $x > y > \Rb$, the proof has:
 \begin{enumerate}
 \item\label{weak-mvp-small} if $\gamma \circ x - \gamma \circ y \preceq 1$, then $\frac{\gamma \circ x - \gamma \circ y}{x - y} \preceq \gamma' \circ y$,
 \item\label{weak-mvp-large} if $\gamma \circ x - \gamma \circ y \succeq 1$, then $(\gamma' \circ y)(x - y) \succeq 1$.
 \end{enumerate}
\end{lem}
yielding a fairly short proof of the main theorem.

